text: tl;dr Pain isn't a one-to-one stimulus-to-response experience. It's incredibly complex&poorly understood. Difficult to treat, but very real.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: So your bodily state intimately affects what's happening in your brain, and your brain imposes top-down processing on pain as well.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: But there are very few places in the body where you don't have neural input & output. The humors of the eyes are the only I can think of.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: And our brain is intimately connected to our bodies. There's no clean division. We pretend there is.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: What we are--our abilities, our personalities--originate in the brain. Cartesian dualism (mind/body dualism) is unnecessary to explain us.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: The phrase "the mind is what the brain does" was coined approx. a lifetime ago (Hebb? I think?). It is uncomfortable, but correct.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: The #1 mistake I think doctors make in thinking about pain is thinking that the mind and body are somehow separate. They are not.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: It's particularly important w/patients who have been silenced & invalidated in other medical interactions.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: Patients are aware of verbal cues. Silence on our part gives them permission to speak.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: We're trained to do everything quickly: get a history quickly, do a physical quickly. But leaving space, leaving silence, helps patients.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: "We can give patients permission to talk to us about difficult subjects"--paraphrasing this lecturer

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: As much as I look up to individual physicians who take on these challenges, the system itself needs to change.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: That's a population of people who NEED care, but the medical reimbursement system incentivizes avoiding providing care for them.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: The family practice physician I shadowed before applying to med school was the only local one who worked w/opiate-addicted pregnant patients

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: Pain is poorly understood at the mechanistic level. So is addiction. We  need more research & more humility in the treatment process.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: BUT medical system needs to compensate appropriately & incentivize that. Right now, it doesn't. 15-min single doc visits are the norm.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: It creates an adversarial dichotomy. Doesn't need to be that way. High-quality interdisciplinary care is possible & works.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: Patients in pain are frustrated by providers who don't believe them. Providers are frustrated by addicted patients & OD deaths.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: It's easy to say "always prescribe opiates" or "never prescribe opiates" but a nuanced decision about what to prescribe & when is necessary.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: I'm really impressed by the quality of our lectures on pain. It's a critical issue--how to treat w/o creating addiction? Answer is complex.

user.description: Med student w/masters in experimental psychology & a decade of research experience in biomedical & psychosocial work. Interests: intersectionality, pugs, cake.
user.name: Kristin Puhl

text: Terms you should know before you analyze data: 1) Mean. 2) Median. 3) Standard deviation. 4) Variance. 5) Linear regression. 6) ANOVA.
